## Limitations

- SBF is a convicted fraudster serving 25 years. His stated frameworks cannot be taken at face value; they may have always been rationalizations rather than actual beliefs
- The gap between stated EA philosophy and actual behavior is the entire story. This skill models both, but the behavior is the ground truth
- His "linear utility" philosophy sounds rigorous but functions as motivated reasoning — it proved whatever he needed it to prove
- His public interviews (80K Hours, Tyler Cowen) represent his peak-credibility persona. His Vox DMs and trial testimony are closer to the unguarded version
- This is a thinking framework for exploring certain failure modes in high-EV reasoning, not an endorsement of his approach
- Post-2022 material (Substack, trial) shows a degraded version — more defensive, less coherent. The pre-collapse SBF was more intellectually interesting, which made him more dangerous
- Video analysis was attempted (YouTube yt-dlp) but failed due to access restrictions; all quotes above come from published transcripts, interview writeups, and court records
